(1157, 256, 'panels_data', 'a:3:{s:7:"widgets";a:2:{i:0;a:6:{s:5:"title";s:0:"";s:4:"text";s:2492:"<h1>-Personal Timeline</h1><h1><img class="wp-image-281 aligncenter" src="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Untitled-2-300x102.png" sizes="(max-width: 761px) 100vw, 761px" srcset="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Untitled-2-300x102.png 300w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Untitled-2-768x262.png 768w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Untitled-2.png 984w" alt="" width="761" height="259" /></h1><h2>Life in Dubai</h2><p>Born in the Newyork of the Middle East, I grew up in a multicultural environement that encouraged innovation. The highrises I would wake up to were, to me, a testament and a reminder of the capacities of the human intellect and the power of human ambition. The large scale projects, thegrand expos and the bussing steets voiced the innovative spirit that Dubai, and consequently I, had. My family and I left Dubai in 2009 following the 2008 recession.<br /> <img class="alignnone wp-image-287" src="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Dubai-Skyline-silhouette-2000x384-300x58.png" sizes="(max-width: 1003px) 100vw, 1003px" srcset="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Dubai-Skyline-silhouette-2000x384-300x58.png 300w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Dubai-Skyline-silhouette-2000x384-1024x197.png 1024w" width="1003" height="194" /></p><h2>Life in Tunisia</h2><p>Far the busy five-laned roads and the sky piercing buildings, the city of Sousse is a quiet and costal city in Tunisia. The quiet however did not remain for long. A year after I moved to Sousse the Tunisian Revolution, nicknamed the "Revolution of the Jasmines", broke out. I witnessed the protests, heard the gunfire and participated in protecting our neighbourhoud.</p><p>Neither my studies nor my moral were hindered due to the move and the subsequent revolution. On the contrary they were strengthened.</p><p><img class=