(395, 1, '2017-01-23 14:17:40', '2017-01-23 14:17:40', '<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-400" src="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/meh.ro9535.jpg" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px" srcset="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/meh.ro9535.jpg 1920w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/meh.ro9535-300x169.jpg 300w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/meh.ro9535-768x432.jpg 768w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/meh.ro9535-1024x576.jpg 1024w" alt="" width="1920" height="1080" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">On the 8th of November of 2016, in a surprising turn of events, business mogul and republican presidential nominee Donald Trump, won the US presidential elections. His victory has been considered as <b>shocking</b> (Business Insider), <b>surprising</b> (The Wall Street Journal), and <b>historic</b> (Financial Times). Nearly all articles, channels, Facebook posts, and tweets have conveyed a general feeling of disbelief. Despite this popular surprise, there is is nothing surprising about Trumps victory. In fact, it could be seen as <b>the most probable all along</b>.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">A number of factors turned the table toward Trumps side, the most important of all perhaps was his opponent: Hillary Clinton herself. Despite leading the polls for a long time, Hillary Clinton, with 59% of Americans disliking the candidate according to the August Washington Post-ABC News polls, was one of the most disliked candidates in the past 30 years second only to Trump himself. Although the hatred directed towards Trump is well-founded, Clintons is a bit more complicated. Firstly, Hillary Clinton represents the so-called Establishment. The Establishment denotes the important and powerful people who control a country or an organization, especially those who support the existing situation (Cambridge Dictionary). It was a general feeling of frustration with the Establishment and a desire for change that eventually led to her downfall. Clinton represented a system that Americans wanted to overturn; the rise of Bernie Sanders also proves the existence of a thirst for change and a need for new blood in the political arena, one of the reasons that led to Barack Obamas historic victory in 2008. Therefore, the outcome of the election has been described as such: the system is broken, Clinton represents that system, and thus, Clinton is broken. But why does she represent the Establishment? She served as First Lady, and is a board member of the Clinton Foundation charity groupone that had transparency issues in the past. She also served as Secretary of State for 5 years, and senator of New York for 6 years. She has been under intense scrutiny for her use of a private email server, the Benghazi embassy attack, and alleged corrupt-ties to Wall Street. Thus, her extensive career and experience in politics constituted both her advantage and her drawback.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">However, the opposing candidate is not the only reason Trump won. Around the world, there has been a general rise in conservative, xenophobic, and nationalist movements, ones that have come to dominate domestic political arenas. From UKIP in Britain, the National Front in France, to Golden Dawn in Greece etc. The rise of toxic politics is not, therefore, an isolated phenomenon. Why are they on the rise? <b>Globalization</b> as Le Pen stated Is a barbarity. These movements appear to focus on immigration, trade, intervention, and global economy. Trump, like Le Pen, attacked the Trans-Pacific Partnership by vowing to abort this initiative, UKIP attacked the European Unions trade deals, Trump attacked immigration laws, UKIP believes in limited, controlled immigration since immigrants are taking our jobs. It is a fear of losing the country to the Latinos, the Mexicans, and the Muslims: a fear that Trump fed on, a fear that he lead by, and a fear that he nurtured. He united people under a common enemy, and a threat that he made clear ever since the beginning of his campaign. Therefore, he was considered steadfast, while Clinton was considered mercurial.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Another very important reason that made his victory a reality is his image as a successful businessman. His self-made empire is a testament to his alleged success, effective management, and leadership potential. Given his wealth, he cannot be bribed, thus he is incorruptible unlike Hillary who needs corporate funding to forward her campaign. He has led a business to success, thus he can lead America to success, unlike Hillary, who, while in office, was involved wars that crippled the economy and will continue with Obamacare that will allegedly destroy the American economy. He is a <b>man</b> who is experienced in negotiating his way through tough deals; he could, therefore, negotiate with the enemies of America and secure American interests, unlike Mrs. Clinton who lost the nuclear arms negotiations with Iran. Whether any of this is actually reasonable is irrelevant, what matters is the image he presents of himself to American voters: an image of power, machismo, determination, and law and order.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">In the end, it comes down to Democracy, and not any Democracy: but American Democracy. Americans do not vote directly for the president. They vote for people, whose number varies between states, that pledgebut are not always legally tiedto vote for the president the state residents voted for. In some states, the winner takes all the electoral votes, in others it is split proportionally between the candidates. It is key to remember that Hillary Clinton <b>won</b> the popular vote: with around 1% more votes. Donald Trump, however, won more states than she did: the <i>right</i> states. This difference in popular votes reflected a 25% difference in electoral votes to Trumps advantage. This is the true reason behind the rage in the US today. It all came down to an arcane, insane eighteenth century idea called the electoral college as Michael Moore put it. This is the second time in the past 16 years that the electoral votes overturned the popular votes: the last time it led to George W. Bushs victory. Today it led to Donald J. Trumps.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Although this is a gross simplification of the many complex factors at play here, these could be the most influential. This election was a fascinating race. Contrary to popular belief it was not a fight between two individuals. It was a fight between two systems of authority, two visions not only of America, but also of the world. The 2016 elections have exposed many sensitive issues within the system, from the electoral college, to immigration, that each side has dissected and brought to the surface.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">This election could be thought of as a fight between two extremes: conformity to the age old Establishment or the acceptance of a radical authoritative change.</span></p>', 'All Hail President T****', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'all-hail-president-t', '', '', '2017-01-23 15:53:59', '2017-01-23 15:53:59', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wp/?p=395', 0, 'post', '', 0),
