(406, 1, '2017-01-23 14:35:00', '2017-01-23 14:35:00', '<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="wp-image-411 aligncenter" src="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Al_Jazeera_Media_Network_logo.png" alt="" width="444" height="257" /> <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-412" src="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Bahrain.jpg" alt="" width="2592" height="1355" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">Few events have been as extensively covered in human history as the Egyptian revolution of the 25th of January. 24/7, news outlets from around the world covered every development, every conflict, every tear and every cheer. The world was hooked on the images of waves of people celebrating, police cars tumbling, military spreading, flags burning, guns firing, protesters running. From CNN to France 24 to the BBC, everyone followed the events as they unfolded; however, one media outlet outshined them all: Al Jazeera. Everyone, starting from the families in Egypt fearing for their lives and the countrys future to the President of the United States Of America, followed Al Jazeeras coverage. Ursula Lindsey, managing editor of the Arabist, wrote that the victory of the revolution, at least in achieving Mubaraks resignation, was accompanied by a discrediting of government-controlled news, a flourishing of homemade media of all sorts and a validation of outlets such as Al Jazeera.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">While we consider these revolutions to be the product of social media, Leila Zahra, an activist who was stationed in Tahrir Square, stated in an interview with the Guardian that: it was [about] much more than those who had access to Twitter and Facebook. If it wasnt for the working class, and the marginalised thousands, this revolution wouldnt have happened. From where do the stated classes receive most of their information, one might ask? Television. Here was Al Jazeeras opportunity to expand their viewership, as a result to its extensive coverage of the Egyptian revolution, as Dr. Lina Khatib, former director of the Carnegie Middle East Center in Beirut, writes.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">With such a portrayal of the Egyptian revolution, Al Jazeera was considered the vanguard for democracy and the defender of Arab freedom (Khatib). An image that it further embraced with the coverage of the Libyan revolution. However, when the Bahrainis started their own uprising, a certain conflict of interest arose and, with it, came the fall of Al Jazeeras status. According to Dr. Khatib, despite the channels support of the Libyan uprising as a legitimate rebellion, its lukewarm position towards the Bahraini revolution seemed contradictory to its image of the champion of Arab freedom. This stance revealed the limits of the channels alleged independence from the Qatari state.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">In her study, Based on the peace journalism model: analysis of Al Jazeeras coverage of Bahrains uprising and Syrias chemical attack, Zainab Abulnabi presents the different aspects of bias that Al-Jazeera committed in its presentation of the Bahraini revolution. An example of this bias would be that neither Al Jazeera America nor Al-Jazeera English classified the uprising as a revolution. Rather, terms like protests (56.9% of articles) and crisis/turmoil (21.5%) were used in describing the situation. The protesters were also classified as Shia opposition (22.5%) but never as revolutionists. Another aspect of this bias is the amount of articles backing the Gulf Cooperation Councils (GCC) intervention in the policing of the revolution.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The Egyptian <img class="alignleft wp-image-409 size-full" src="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Untitled-e1485182560628.png" width="418" height="227" />revolution achieved its main goal of overthrowing Mubaraks regime. It was well portrayed internationally and thus accumulated a worldwide support. In Bahrain, however, 122 deaths and 2,708 injuries later, the royal family remains in power, therefore the revolution has failed. Which gives Al Jazeera the opportunity to question: Was Bahrain''s uprising worth it? and then to voice: It was not a revolution, but rather a planned coup.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">With this comparison in mind, can we go as far as saying that Al Jazeeras, and other outlets, coverage of these two revolutions resulted in their respective demise or victory? I believe that to limit it to the TV and newspaper coverage would not honor the triumph of the Egyptian nor discredit the Bahraini governments and the GCCs inhumane actions. However, to disregard the medias role in the success or failure of modern revolutions would be a major mistake. One media outlet can make a difference. One people, however, can make even more of a difference.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><i>Special thanks to Zainab Abulnabi for her exquisite analysis from which most of the sources are derived.</i></p>', 'One Outlet, Two Revolutions', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'one-outlet-two-revolutions', '', '', '2017-01-23 15:53:24', '2017-01-23 15:53:24', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wp/?p=406', 0, 'post', '', 0),
