(427, 1, '2017-01-23 15:11:51', '2017-01-23 15:11:51', '<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-416" src="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/date-ramadan-debut-ramadan.png" alt="" width="1020" height="320" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">213 years ago, one of the worlds most renowned philosophers claimed God is dead. It meant not that God died in the literal sense but that societies of the post-enlightened era began to move away from God for they have killed him. His intention, however, was not blasphemy but awakening. His goal was to announce that the death of religion was inevitable. An idea shared by many philosophers like Friedrich Hegel who had the feeling that God Himself is dead.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">How does that relate to our world today? Is this prophecy being fulfilled?</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">A study conducted by Duke and University College London proved that religious affiliation in the US has dropped by 23% between those born before 1935 and those born after 1975. They concluded that If you break it down over five-year chunks, each age group is a little less religious than the one before it*. This phenomenon isnt restricted to the US. Despite our claims of being a very religious region that takes pride in its spirituality, we can no longer hold this title without reviewing our current behavior.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">One could argue that Ramadan, along with Hajj, is the epitome of Muslim spirituality. Despite the honorable status that Ramadan has in the soul of every Muslim, it has changed in many ways and in many regions of the Muslim world. I make this claim since I have had the opportunity of spending Ramadan in three Arab and Muslim-majority countries (Tunisia, UAE and Egypt).</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Perhaps the most important reason that Ramadan has undergone this radical metamorphosis is due to the introduction of Ramadan series. A full fledged media war between television channels that compete over the viewership of this holy month. By the end of the month they recite their respective viewer counts as though it was the Oscars transforming the month into nothing more than a business opportunity. It is also particularly interesting to state that its during Ramadan that commercial TV channels get their highest ratings of the year. For example, a record 85 million Arab viewers tuned in on the 30th of August of 2008 to watch the final episode of <i>Nour </i>according to MBC figures.*****</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">As a result of this flood of Ramadan TV series (more than 100 series available across a multitude of channels), from my experience, I have noticed that iftar discussions have shifted from those centred around faith and tradition, towards more trivial matters such as recent developments on a particular television series.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Thus we see websites posting headlines like :</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">25 RAMADAN SERIES YOU CANT MISS THIS YEAR</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Ramadan''s coming; grab your konafa bel eshta and munch on it while watching some of this year''s exciting mosalsalaat.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">And:</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Somewhere beyond the fasting, iftar with the family, and the religious aspects of Ramadan are nights full of grabbing a plate, creating a mountain of food (or basboosa), and staring at the TV for hours watching different shows and series. It''s one of things we look forward to most about the season, but with countless different shows it''s hard to keep up! **</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Some may argue that these gatherings bring the family together , since, it is at this time that the parents ,tired from a day of fasting and work, get to relax in the living room with their children appreciating each other''s company. So Ramadan has become so commercialized to the point that ,I believe, it has almost undergone the same transformation that christmas in the US underwent. By the introduction of Ramadan centric products like the Red Velvet konafa, the Ramadan deals,and MC Donalds <i>sohour </i>not only have the TV outlets abused the holy month but the food outlets well. Thus, transforming it into a fast food extravaganza.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Furthermore, the spirit of Ramadan appears to be dying because the habits followed by most Muslims during the holy month undermine its very goals. The most important of these is without a doubt the habit of overeating after breaking the fast. This phenomenon is visible through the fact that hundreds of people have been admitted to emergency rooms in the UAE**** in the Ramadan of 2015.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Not only is the amount of food on the table at iftar considerably bigger than any regular meal one would have in a regular day, but also the habit of binge eating till sohour completely beats the purpose of the month. Thus, Muslims, who were supposed to be empathising with the poor by minimising their food and water intake, end up gaining more weight at the end of the month. For example the Ahram Weekly reported that according to the National Centre for Social and Criminal Research (NCSCR), 83 per cent of Egyptian families alter their food consumption habits during Ramadan in a way that augments their food bill for this month by 50 to 100 per cent.******</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">This is directly related to another unhealthy habit common amongst young adults: that of sleeping all day and waking at the sound of the <i>adhan</i>. With the religious implications of this act aside, and from a very objective vantage point, it seems hypocritical to claim fasting after having spent the whole day at a minimal metabolism and effort.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Moreover, one could argue that the rise of systematized charity has had a hand in the desensibilization of the upper and upper-middle class towards the poor and economically disadvantaged. Since the act of giving is conducted by an intermediary, it is easier to feel detached from the cause on a personal level. The simplicity of zakat has in such a matter caused it to lose its value. This systematized approach, however, has made it much easier to reach those in need and thus the goal of <i>zakat</i> is better achieved through charity associations.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Another extremely dangerous phenomenon is the withdrawal syndrome due to abstaining from smoking. Given that over one billion people are smokers***, the prevalence of withdrawal symptoms has become a major one in Muslim homes where at least one member of the family ( in most cases ) is a smoker. We have all seen or heard of those horrid symptoms that include anger, anxiety, insomnia and depression. Thus, acts that oppose the essence of the month are committed, for Experts claimed that increases in blood crimes (+1.5%) and theft (+3.5%) are mainly the result of abstinence from smoke.*******</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">With all what has been said in mind, where does the Muslim world go next ? Will it acknowledge that change is part of any custom ? Or will it preserve it by conserving its original form?</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Or is the aforementioned prophecy being fulfilled?</span></p>', 'Ramadan is dead', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '414-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-01-23 15:11:51', '2017-01-23 15:11:51', '', 414, 'http://localhost/wp/2017/01/23/414-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(428, 1, '2017-01-23 15:46:44', '2017-01-23 15:46:44', '<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-400" src="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/meh.ro9535.jpg" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px" srcset="http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/meh.ro9535.jpg 1920w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/meh.ro9535-300x169.jpg 300w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/meh.ro9535-768x432.jpg 768w, http://localhost/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/meh.ro9535-1024x576.jpg 1024w" alt="" width="1920" height="1080" /></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">On the 8th of November of 2016, in a surprising turn of events, business mogul and republican presidential nominee Donald Trump, won the US presidential elections. His victory has been considered as <b>shocking</b> (Business Insider), <b>surprising</b> (The Wall Street Journal), and <b>historic</b> (Financial Times). Nearly all articles, channels, Facebook posts, and tweets have conveyed a general feeling of disbelief. Despite this popular surprise, there is is nothing surprising about Trumps victory. In fact, it could be seen as <b>the most probable all along</b>.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">A number of factors turned the table toward Trumps side, the most important of all perhaps was his opponent: Hillary Clinton herself. Despite leading the polls for a long time, Hillary Clinton, with 59% of Americans disliking the candidate according to the August Washington Post-ABC News polls, was one of the most disliked candidates in the past 30 years second only to Trump himself. Although the hatred directed towards Trump is well-founded, Clintons is a bit more complicated. Firstly, Hillary Clinton represents the so-called Establishment. The Establishment denotes the important and powerful people who control a country or an organization, especially those who support the existing situation (Cambridge Dictionary). It was a general feeling of frustration with the Establishment and a desire for change that eventually led to her downfall. Clinton represented a system that Americans wanted to overturn; the rise of Bernie Sanders also proves the existence of a thirst for change and a need for new blood in the political arena, one of the reasons that led to Barack Obamas historic victory in 2008. Therefore, the outcome of the election has been described as such: the system is broken, Clinton represents that system, and thus, Clinton is broken. But why does she represent the Establishment? She served as First Lady, and is a board member of the Clinton Foundation charity groupone that had transparency issues in the past. She also served as Secretary of State for 5 years, and senator of New York for 6 years. She has been under intense scrutiny for her use of a private email server, the Benghazi embassy attack, and alleged corrupt-ties to Wall Street. Thus, her extensive career and experience in politics constituted both her advantage and her drawback.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">However, the opposing candidate is not the only reason Trump won. Around the world, there has been a general rise in conservative, xenophobic, and nationalist movements, ones that have come to dominate domestic political arenas. From UKIP in Britain, the National Front in France, to Golden Dawn in Greece etc. The rise of toxic politics is not, therefore, an isolated phenomenon. Why are they on the rise? <b>Globalization</b> as Le Pen stated Is a barbarity. These movements appear to focus on immigration, trade, intervention, and global economy. Trump, like Le Pen, attacked the Trans-Pacific Partnership by vowing to abort this initiative, UKIP attacked the European Unions trade deals, Trump attacked immigration laws, UKIP believes in limited, controlled immigration since immigrants are taking our jobs. It is a fear of losing the country to the Latinos, the Mexicans, and the Muslims: a fear that Trump fed on, a fear that he lead by, and a fear that he nurtured. He united people under a common enemy, and a threat that he made clear ever since the beginning of his campaign. Therefore, he was considered steadfast, while Clinton was considered mercurial.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Another very important reason that made his victory a reality is his image as a successful businessman. His self-made empire is a testament to his alleged success, effective management, and leadership potential. Given his wealth, he cannot be bribed, thus he is incorruptible unlike Hillary who needs corporate funding to forward her campaign. He has led a business to success, thus he can lead America to success, unlike Hillary, who, while in office, was involved wars that crippled the economy and will continue with Obamacare that will allegedly destroy the American economy. He is a <b>man</b> who is experienced in negotiating his way through tough deals; he could, therefore, negotiate with the enemies of America and secure American interests, unlike Mrs. Clinton who lost the nuclear arms negotiations with Iran. Whether any of this is actually reasonable is irrelevant, what matters is the image he presents of himself to American voters: an image of power, machismo, determination, and law and order.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">In the end, it comes down to Democracy, and not any Democracy: but American Democracy. Americans do not vote directly for the president. They vote for people, whose number varies between states, that pledgebut are not always legally tiedto vote for the president the state residents voted for. In some states, the winner takes all the electoral votes, in others it is split proportionally between the candidates. It is key to remember that Hillary Clinton <b>won</b> the popular vote: with around 1% more votes. Donald Trump, however, won more states than she did: the <i>right</i> states. This difference in popular votes reflected a 25% difference in electoral votes to Trumps advantage. This is the true reason behind the rage in the US today. It all came down to an arcane, insane eighteenth century idea called the electoral college as Michael Moore put it. This is the second time in the past 16 years that the electoral votes overturned the popular votes: the last time it led to George W. Bushs victory. Today it led to Donald J. Trumps.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">Although this is a gross simplification of the many complex factors at play here, these could be the most influential. This election was a fascinating race. Contrary to popular belief it was not a fight between two individuals. It was a fight between two systems of authority, two visions not only of America, but also of the world. The 2016 elections have exposed many sensitive issues within the system, from the electoral college, to immigration, that each side has dissected and brought to the surface.</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="color: #000000;">This election could be thought of as a fight between two extremes: conformity to the age old Establishment or the acceptance of a radical authoritative change.</span></p>', 'All Hail President T****', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '395-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-01-23 15:46:44', '2017-01-23 15:46:44', '', 395, 'http://localhost/wp/2017/01/23/395-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
